title: For Trade:  Gen 1 night scope, and other items for trade
postcontent:
I have a very lightly used generation 1 night vision scope.  These retail for around $200.  They are the basic level night vision optics, but operate effectively.  Mil spec gen 2 or 3 are going to run anywhere from $500-2000.  If you are interesting in trading varmint tipped .223 ammo, preferrably hornady then please shoot me a reply.  Please don't send me unreasonable offers, I have been buying ammo before the fad and actually need this stuff.  I figure this is worth around 120-150 rds of varmint depending on brand and what kind it is.  I'm not trying to make any money or lose any so if you have a fair trade and are interested I'm your guy.

It's kind of crappy when you go to 5 different sporting goods stores and can't even buy any of the ammo your looking for and you see 20 guys on here that probably aren't even interested in shooting and just want to make a buck.  I guess you can argue either way,and I have seen people saying its messed up, and I have seen people defending their actions based on free market ideals.  I can see both ways, but to the one who is saying its a free market and supply and demand that's great and all but also when you guys are buying up all of it at cabelas and other places and sit on it you are manipulating the supply. Really there are plenty,and the ammo stores are churning out more than ever.  It's just people realize they can charge 2-3 times what the retail cost is that is messed up.  Anyway I'm going to wind down my rant.

This is what I have to trade plus night vision monocular:

title: For Sale:  Riverside Arms Single Shot 12 Gauge
postcontent:
This Riverside Arms 12 Gauge is a single shot.  I've seen it called a "Goose Gun."  I took this shotgun by the local range today, Feb 20th, and upon inspection they said that it is in excellent condition, and appears to have been fired very little. It is still tight and 100% functional.  After some research, I found that Riverside arms was a trade name owned by J. Stevens Arms Company who purchased Crescent Arms, and who was later bought by Savage who produced them until 1948. (This is the best information I can find, however I do not know the accuracy of it as such so the buyer should do due diligence)  Being that this gun was manufactured prior to 1968, it doesn't have a serial number since they weren't required.  These models were what was considered the "hardware store" version of the Stevens shotguns.  They weren't the "top tier" line quality units.  A little less refined after milling, they were designed to be more affordable given that they were produced from the turn of the century through the great depression and up until WWII.  While considered a "second Tier" gun, this was simply the finish (not luxurious) and not indicative of poor quality materials.  Many people still shoot Riverside products to this day, and replacement parts are still available.  While not overly valuable, the craftsmanship was built to last.

title: For Sale:  Remington 740 with 4 and 10 round magazines
postcontent:
For sale is a classic Remington 740 Woodsmaster chambered in 30-06.  

Refinished stock and refinished barrel.  Total scrub down of action and barrel making it clean and smooth as it should be.  This gun may have been owned by your grandpa, but looks like you are buying a vintage remake of something new out of the store.  See pictures on the refinish work.  7  pounds, 22 inch barrel.

Sights:  Comes equipped with weaver style mount (not pictured) and the mounting screws.  This 740 is a very serviceable firearm though without a scope using the white metal bead front ramp and the step-adjustable semi-buckhorn rear.

What sets this 740 apart from all the others you see for sale on Gunbroker and on Armslist are two things 1) is the attention to refinishing the stock that was used.  The purchaser of this gun will have a one of a kind.  The flame maple you see was brought out through careful selection of oils and waxes.  The final finish that has been applied makes this a hunt-worthy gun that will stand up to the elements.  There is a hairline crack that has been there for years, and is not growing due to it being repaired long before my ownership.  On ebay people sell unfinished 740 stock blanks for over $225.  Anyone owning this gun has a great hunting rifle that you will be proud to have others see.  The great part of the finish that I chose for this, is it doesnt give up its heritage old looking feel.  It just looks like something bought 50 years ago and stored well.

And number 2) this firearm comes equipped with the regular 4 round magazine as well as the 10 round magazine.  The ten round magazine is not bulky, fits well, and is a great addition to bring the extra firepower you want with you on a long hunt.  New 10 round magazines that fit the 740 run from 50-80 dollars.  Its just fun to have a 10 round 30-06 too!  Great for hunting in those tight woods where you have minimal time to get off the second shot.  And great for those shots where you need to throw a lot of lead at a deer booking across a field.

title: For Sale:  InterArms .22 ATD LR Take Down rifle
postcontent:
This InterArms .22 ATD LR is in superb condition showing no signs of even normal wear.  The barrel is in excellent condition.  This gun is 99.9%.  It is a Norinco and imported by Interarms from 1987 to 1996.  This gun was a copy of the ever desirable Browning SA22.  The wood is not as fancy as the Browning, and the scroll work on the receiver is not as detailed, but this gun could be bought for half what the Browning name brand costs. Other than the esthetics , I cannot find a lot of differences between the two.  This gun does have an interesting and rarer feature, the ability to load through the stock.  Finish is great and still like factory new.  After an in depth inspection by myself, a couple of other collectors, and a local gunsmith, I can confidently say we don't believe it had ever been fired.  Email me with any questions.  $300  Cash only, no trades.

4/23/2013 Update  I was going to keep this little rifle, and decided to shoot it.  It fired well except that it had a couple hiccups loading, which after a gunsmith had a look at it was determined that the factory milling had left a bit of a sharp edge in the receiver and the casings would sometimes catch.  I've since had that remedied and decided I don't really need another .22 as I already have 3.  It's a beautiful little gun, and I've received many compliments on it while I've had it at the range.  I also learned about the take-down feature on this gun, and anyone can disassemble this gun in less than 30 seconds.  It's simplicity has to be the most desirable part of the design.

I am liquidating a couple collection of firearms.  I have several shotguns, a black powder revolver, and a couple black powder rifles.   I will consider selling the collection in lots.  All meetings to view any of these guns will take place at Bullseye Marksman Gun Club in Cumming.  They are located just off GA400 exit 13.  Please do not bother to email and ask me to meet elsewhere as I will not respond.  Also, the reason I list a price is that is what I am selling it for.  Don't email and ask me "what is your best price" as I can tell you now, my price is what you see here.  (I have researched prices on all these firearms in depth and determined these asking prices to be more than reasonable) Also, if the ad is up, it's still for sale.  I don't meet there for the purpose of transfers, it's just a safe location for both buyer and seller.  I will need to see a valid GA drivers license, and would like to see a GA CWL.  As with any firearm sale, I reserve the right to not sell to anyone, especially those who I deem as sketchy.
